Urban Design and Physical Activity
Author: Nidhi Kanchepalle
Level: Intermediate
Skills: Python, Exploratory Data Analysis, Data Visualisation
Duration: {90} minutes
Scenario

This use case explores how urban design influences physical activity across Melbourne by analysing open datasets on pedestrian counts, footpaths, playgrounds, residential profiles, building footprints, and suburb boundaries. The objective is to uncover spatial and temporal patterns in pedestrian movement and examine how various elements of the built environment contribute to walking behaviour. The pedestrian counts data spans from 2023 to 2025, providing a recent view of foot traffic trends across the city. By integrating geospatial and demographic data—including building footprints that reveal density, height, and structure types—the analysis aims to identify suburbs that promote higher levels of physical activity and understand the role of infrastructure—such as well-connected footpaths, access to recreational areas, and population distribution—in shaping these trends. The insights derived from this study can help urban planners make informed, evidence-based decisions to design healthier, more walkable neighbourhoods that encourage active lifestyles.

What This Use Case Will Teach You

At the end of this use case, you will be able to:

  • Learn how to load data using APIs
  • Handle missing values and prepare the data for meaningful analysis
  • Use grouping, filtering, and aggregation techniques to uncover patterns and trends
  • Perform spatial joins and analyse geospatial data using GeoPandas
  • Visualise temporal and spatial trends using appropriate charts and maps
  • Identify correlations between infrastructure features and pedestrian activity
  • Generate actionable insights to inform urban planning decisions
Background / Introduction

Urban planning plays a crucial role in shaping how people interact with their surroundings, especially when it comes to promoting active lifestyles. Walkable neighbourhoods with accessible footpaths, green spaces, and recreational areas are more likely to encourage residents to engage in physical activity. As cities grow, there is a growing need for data-driven approaches to understand how urban design influences movement patterns and community well-being.

This use case aims to explore the relationship between urban infrastructure and physical activity levels, using pedestrian count data. By integrating multiple open datasets—such as pedestrian count data, footpath networks, playground locations, building footprints, suburb boundaries, and demographic profiles—we aim to uncover trends and spatial patterns that highlight how the built environment impacts walking behaviour.

Through this analysis, urban planners and decision-makers can gain insights into which areas support active lifestyles and where improvements in infrastructure could have the most impact. The ultimate goal is to use data to inform more effective urban design strategies that prioritise health, accessibility, and sustainability across Melbourne's suburbs.

Importing Data Through API¶

In [104]:
with open("API_Key.txt", "r", encoding="utf-8-sig") as f:
    API_KEY = f.read().strip()

# Define API data fetching function
def API_upload(dataset_key):
    base_url = 'https://data.melbourne.vic.gov.au/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/'
    format = 'csv'
    full_url = f'{base_url}{dataset_key}/exports/{format}'

    params = {
        'select': '*',
        'timezone': 'UTC',
        'lang': 'en',
        'limit': '-1'
    }

    headers = {
        'X-App-Token': API_KEY
    }

    response = requests.get(full_url, params=params, headers=headers)
    if response.status_code == 200:
        content = response.content.decode('utf-8')
        df = pd.read_csv(StringIO(content), delimiter=';')
        df['SOURCE_DATASET'] = dataset_key
        return df
    else:
        print(f"Error fetching data from {full_url}: {response.status_code}")
        return pd.DataFrame()

data_sets = {
    "pedestrian_counts": ['pedestrian-counting-system-monthly-counts-per-hour'],
    "building_footprints": ['2023-building-footprints'],
    "playgrounds": ['playgrounds'],
    "footpaths": ['footpaths'],
    "resident_profiles": ['residents-profiles-by-clue-small-area']
}

pedestrian_counts_df = pd.concat([API_upload(ds) for ds in data_sets["pedestrian_counts"]], ignore_index=True)
building_footprints_df = pd.concat([API_upload(ds) for ds in data_sets["building_footprints"]], ignore_index=True)
playgrounds_df = pd.concat([API_upload(ds) for ds in data_sets["playgrounds"]], ignore_index=True)
footpaths_df = pd.concat([API_upload(ds) for ds in data_sets["footpaths"]], ignore_index=True)
resident_profiles_df = pd.concat([API_upload(ds) for ds in data_sets["resident_profiles"]], ignore_index=True)

Inspecting Data¶

The pedestrian counts dataset contains hourly foot traffic data recorded by sensors installed at various locations across Melbourne. Each entry includes the date, hour, sensor location, counts in both directions, and total pedestrian activity. This data is useful for identifying spatial and temporal trends in pedestrian movement, such as peak walking hours or high-traffic areas.

The footpaths dataset contains geospatial information about public footpaths across Melbourne, including their location, geometry, asset classification, and source of data collection. Each record represents a footpath segment and includes attributes like road segment ID, mapping method, and asset condition. This dataset is useful for measuring walkability, identifying areas with greater footpath access, and supporting urban planning decisions aimed at improving pedestrian connectivity and infrastructure.

Analysing Pedestrian Activity¶

In this step, I then used grouping and aggregation to calculate average pedestrian counts over time periods and visualised the trends using relevant plots to observe patterns in hourly, daily, and monthly pedestrian activity.

In [119]:
pedestrian_counts_df['sensing_date'] = pd.to_datetime(pedestrian_counts_df['sensing_date'])
pedestrian_counts_df['hour'] = pedestrian_counts_df['hourday'].astype(int)
pedestrian_counts_df['day_of_week'] = pedestrian_counts_df['sensing_date'].dt.day_name()
pedestrian_counts_df['month'] = pedestrian_counts_df['sensing_date'].dt.month_name()

# Hourly trend
hourly_avg = pedestrian_counts_df.groupby('hour')['pedestriancount'].mean().reset_index()
sns.lineplot(data=hourly_avg, x='hour', y='pedestriancount')
plt.title("Average Pedestrian Count by Hour")
plt.xlabel("Hour")
plt.ylabel("Average Count")
plt.xticks(range(0, 24))
plt.show()

# Daily trend
daily_avg = pedestrian_counts_df.groupby('day_of_week')['pedestriancount'].mean().reset_index()
sns.barplot(data=daily_avg, x='day_of_week', y='pedestriancount',order=['Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday','Saturday','Sunday'])
plt.title("Average Pedestrian Count by Day")
plt.xlabel("Day of Week")
plt.ylabel("Average Count")
plt.show()

# Monthly trend
monthly_avg = pedestrian_counts_df.groupby('month')['pedestriancount'].mean().reset_index()
sns.barplot(data=monthly_avg, x='month', y='pedestriancount',order=['January','February','March','April','May','June','July','August','September','October','November','December'])
plt.title("Average Pedestrian Count by Month")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

The above plots show clear temporal trends in pedestrian activity across Melbourne. Pedestrian counts peak during morning and evening hours, especially around 8 AM and 5–6 PM, reflecting typical commute times. Daily trends show higher activity from Wednesday to Saturday, with slightly lower counts on Mondays and Sundays. Monthly analysis indicates that March and December experience the highest pedestrian volumes, possibly due to events or seasonal factors, while the lowest counts occur in June and July, aligning with colder winter months.

Analysing Playground Proximity for Pedestrian Activity¶

The below code matches each pedestrian sensor with its nearest playground, calculates the walking distance, and flags whether the sensor is within 800 m of a playground to study how playground proximity may influence pedestrian activity.

plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (10, 6)

def to_projected(gdf, epsg_m=7855):
    gdf = gdf.set_crs(4326, allow_override=True) if gdf.crs is None else gdf.to_crs(4326)
    return gdf.to_crs(epsg=epsg_m)

def plot_group_timeseries(df, group_col, y_col='pedestriancount', x_col='hour', title=''):
    pivot = df.pivot_table(index=x_col, columns=group_col, values=y_col, aggfunc='mean')
    pivot.plot(marker='o')
    plt.title(title); plt.xlabel(x_col.capitalize()); plt.ylabel(f'Avg {y_col}')
    plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3); plt.show()

# ===== Pedestrian points =====

Analysing Apartment Share from Resident Profiles and Pedestrian Activity¶

This code takes the resident profiles data to calculate the share of apartments in Greater Melbourne by year. It then combines this with yearly pedestrian counts, matches years between the two datasets, and finally checks if there is a relationship between apartment share and pedestrian activity using a scatter plot.

In [135]:
rp = resident_profiles_df.copy()
rp['year']  = pd.to_numeric(rp['year'], errors='coerce')
rp['value'] = pd.to_numeric(rp['value'], errors='coerce')

gm = rp[rp['geography'].str.contains('Greater Melbourne', case=False, na=False)]
if gm.empty:
    gm = rp[rp['geography'].str.contains('Melbourne', case=False, na=False)]

is_dwell = (
    gm['topic'].str.contains('Dwellings', case=False, na=False) &
    gm['category'].str.contains('Dwelling type - detailed', case=False, na=False) &
    gm['value_description'].eq('Count of occupied private dwellings')
)
dw = gm.loc[is_dwell, ['year','sub_category','value']].copy()

tot = dw.groupby('year', as_index=False)['value'].sum().rename(columns={'value':'total_dw'})
apt = (dw[dw['sub_category'].str.contains('apartment|flat', case=False, na=False)]
       .groupby('year', as_index=False)['value'].sum()
       .rename(columns={'value':'apt_dw'}))
res_feat = tot.merge(apt, on='year', how='left')
res_feat['apartment_share'] = res_feat['apt_dw'] / res_feat['total_dw']
res_feat = res_feat[['year','apartment_share']].drop_duplicates().dropna(subset=['year'])

# ---------- 2) Pedestrian: city-wide by year
ped = pedestrian_counts_df.copy()
ped['sensing_date'] = pd.to_datetime(ped['sensing_date'], errors='coerce')
ped = ped.dropna(subset=['sensing_date','pedestriancount'])
ped['year'] = ped['sensing_date'].dt.year

ped_year = (ped.groupby('year', as_index=False)['pedestriancount']
              .agg(ped_mean='mean', ped_sum='sum', ped_count='size'))

# ---------- 3) Carry-forward resident year to each ped year
avail = np.sort(res_feat['year'].dropna().unique())
def carry_forward(y):
    prev = avail[avail <= y]
    return prev.max() if prev.size else (avail.min() if avail.size else np.nan)

ped_year['res_year'] = ped_year['year'].apply(carry_forward)

merged = ped_year.merge(res_feat.rename(columns={'year':'res_year'}),
                        on='res_year', how='left')

print("Merged preview:\n", merged.head())
print("Rows with apartment_share:", merged['apartment_share'].notna().sum(), "/", len(merged))

have = merged.dropna(subset=['apartment_share'])
if len(have) >= 2:
    corr = have[['ped_mean','apartment_share']].corr(method='spearman').loc['ped_mean','apartment_share']
    # Scatter with best-fit line
    x = have['apartment_share'].to_numpy()

Estimating the Effect of Playground Proximity on Pedestrian Activity¶

This code creates a daily dataset per sensor, labels sensors near a playground as the “treatment” (T=1), and then uses Coarsened Exact Matching (CEM) on time (month, weekday) and coarse location (lat/lon quantiles) to compute the ATT—the average difference in daily pedestrian counts between near vs. far sensors within comparable strata.

In [136]:
df = ped_near[['id','sensor_name','sensing_date','day_of_week','lat','lon',
               'pedestriancount','dist_to_playground_m'] +
              [c for c in ped_near.columns if str(c).startswith('near_playground_')]].copy()

df['sensing_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['sensing_date'], errors='coerce')
df = df.dropna(subset=['sensing_date','pedestriancount'])

near_col = next((c for c in df.columns if str(c).startswith('near_playground_')
                 and set(df[c].dropna().unique()).issubset({0,1})), None)
if near_col is None:
    raise KeyError("No binary proximity flag found. Expected a column like 'near_playground_800m'.")

# --- Daily outcome per sensor (silence future warning) ---
daily = (df.groupby(['sensor_name','sensing_date','day_of_week'], as_index=False, observed=False)
           ['pedestriancount'].mean()
           .rename(columns={'pedestriancount':'y'}))

# Treatment + coordinates at sensor level
sensor_T  = df.groupby('sensor_name', as_index=False, observed=False)[near_col].max().rename(columns={near_col:'T'})
sensor_xy = (df.groupby('sensor_name', as_index=False, observed=False)
               .agg(lat=('lat','mean'), lon=('lon','mean')))

xy = (daily.merge(sensor_T,  on='sensor_name', how='left')
           .merge(sensor_xy, on='sensor_name', how='left'))
xy['T'] = xy['T'].fillna(0).astype(int)
xy['month'] = xy['sensing_date'].dt.month
# if day_of_week missing/NaN, derive from date
if 'day_of_week' not in xy or xy['day_of_week'].isna().all():
    xy['day_of_week'] = xy['sensing_date'].dt.day_name()
xy['day_of_week'] = xy['day_of_week'].astype(str)

print("Treated obs:", int((xy['T']==1).sum()), "| Control obs:", int((xy['T']==0).sum()))

def cem_att(frame, keys):
    g = frame.groupby(keys + ['T'], observed=False)['y'].mean().unstack()
    n = frame.groupby(keys + ['T'], observed=False)['y'].size().unstack().fillna(0)
    valid = g.dropna()                   # strata with BOTH T=0 and T=1
    if valid.empty:
        return np.nan, 0, 0
    att_s = (valid[1] - valid[0])        # diff in means per stratum
    w = n.loc[valid.index, 1]            # weight by treated count (ATT)
    ATT = (att_s * w).sum() / (w.sum() if w.sum() else np.nan)
    return ATT, len(valid), int(w.sum())


def qbins(s, q=5):
    q = min(q, s.nunique(dropna=True)) if s.notna().any() else 1
    if q < 2:
        return pd.Series(['ALL']*len(s), index=s.index)
    return pd.qcut(s, q=q, duplicates='drop').astype(str)

xy = xy.copy()
xy['lat_q'] = qbins(xy['lat'], q=5)
xy['lon_q'] = qbins(xy['lon'], q=5)

# Try from most specific to most general
key_sets = [
    ['month','day_of_week','lat_q','lon_q'],
    ['month','lat_q','lon_q'],
    ['month','day_of_week'],
    ['month']
]

ATT = np.nan; used = None; strata_used = 0; treated_used = 0
for keys in key_sets:
    att, k, tw = cem_att(xy, keys)
    if not np.isnan(att):
        ATT, used, strata_used, treated_used = att, keys, k, tw
        break

if used is not None:
    print(f"✓ CEM ATT computed over keys {used} | Strata used: {strata_used} | Treated obs used: {treated_used}")
    print(f"ATT (near - far) on daily mean ped count ≈ {ATT:.2f}")
else:
    print("No overlapping strata even after coarsening → falling back to fast OLS adjustment.")

    # --- Fallback: tiny OLS with month & DOW dummies + lat/lon continuous ---
    xy2 = xy.dropna(subset=['y']).copy()
    xy2['lat_s'] = (xy2['lat'] - xy2['lat'].mean()) / (xy2['lat'].std(ddof=0) or 1)
    xy2['lon_s'] = (xy2['lon'] - xy2['lon'].mean()) / (xy2['lon'].std(ddof=0) or 1)

    X = pd.get_dummies(xy2[['month','day_of_week']], drop_first=True)
    X = pd.concat([
        pd.Series(1.0, index=xy2.index, name='intercept'),
        xy2['T'].astype(float).rename('T'),
        xy2[['lat_s','lon_s']].astype(float),
        X
    ], axis=1)

    Y = xy2['y'].to_numpy(dtype=float)
    beta, *_ = np.linalg.lstsq(X.to_numpy(dtype=float), Y, rcond=None)
    tau = float(beta[1])  # coefficient on T

    print(f"OLS adjusted effect of proximity (tau) ≈ {tau:.2f}  (units: daily mean ped count)")

For planning or investment decisions aimed at boosting walking, the evidence points toward focusing on land-use intensity, connectivity to transit, and commercial frontage rather than playground proximity alone.

Clustering Pedestrian Sensors by Activity and Playground Proximity¶

This code creates a feature set for each pedestrian sensor using its average count, variability, distance to the nearest playground, coordinates, and a binary flag for being within 800 m of a playground. The features are scaled and then grouped into 3 clusters using K-Means. The result helps to identify different types of sensor locations (e.g., consistently busy, moderately active, or quieter sites) and whether playground proximity plays a role in how sensors group together.

          .agg(dist_to_playground_m=('dist_to_playground_m','min'),
               lat=('lat','mean'), lon=('lon','mean'))

feat = base.merge(near, on='sensor_name', how='left')

# Select features and scale

km = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init='auto')
feat['cluster'] = km.fit_predict(X_scaled)

Detecting Unusual Pedestrian Days¶

This code builds a daily per-sensor table and adds simple context features (month, weekend flag, distance to nearest playground). It scales the features and uses Isolation Forest to flag anomalous days where pedestrian counts are unexpectedly high/low given the context. The output lists the top unusual sensor-days with their anomaly scores so we can investigate events, data issues, or special conditions.

def anomaly_summary(Xy):
    a = Xy[Xy['anomaly']==1].copy()
    if a.empty:
        print("No anomalies flagged."); 
        return pd.DataFrame()

    a['sensing_date'] = pd.to_datetime(a['sensing_date'])
    a['dow']   = a['sensing_date'].dt.day_name()
    a['month'] = a['sensing_date'].dt.month

    # Baseline per sensor to measure "excess"
    med = Xy.groupby('sensor_name')['y'].median().rename('y_median').reset_index()
    a = a.merge(med, on='sensor_name', how='left')
    a['excess'] = a['y'] - a['y_median']

    # Sensor-level digest
    summary = (a.groupby('sensor_name', as_index=False)
                 .agg(
                     n_anoms=('anomaly','size'),
                     max_score=('anomaly_score','max'),
                     mean_excess=('excess','mean'),
                     top_month=('month', lambda s: s.value_counts().idxmax()),
                     top_dow=('dow',   lambda s: s.value_counts().idxmax())
                 )
               .sort_values(['n_anoms','max_score'], ascending=[False, False]))

    # Top 15 anomaly rows for quick viewing
    top_rows = a.sort_values('anomaly_score', ascending=False)\
                .loc[:, ['sensor_name','sensing_date','y','excess','anomaly_score']]\
                .head(15)

    print("— Sensor-level summary —")
    print(summary.head(12))
    print("\n— Top 15 anomaly rows —")
    print(top_rows)
    return summary

This function plots each sensor’s daily counts over a ±28-day window around a chosen date, overlays a 7-day rolling median as baseline, and marks the anomaly day. It also compares the hourly profile on the anomaly day with the typical same-weekday pattern, so we can visualise when (and how strongly) the spike deviates from normal

In [141]:
def plot_anomaly_window(sensor_id, date_str, window_days=28):
    day = pd.to_datetime(date_str)

    # Daily series for this sensor
    d0 = (pedestrian_counts_df[['sensor_name','sensing_date','pedestriancount']]
            .query("sensor_name == @sensor_id")
            .assign(sensing_date=lambda x: pd.to_datetime(x['sensing_date']))
            .groupby('sensing_date', observed=False)['pedestriancount'].mean()
            .asfreq('D').fillna(0.0))

    # Window around the anomaly day
    lo, hi = day - pd.Timedelta(days=window_days), day + pd.Timedelta(days=window_days)
    dwin = d0.loc[lo:hi]

    # Rolling baseline + highlight anomaly
    roll = d0.rolling(7, center=True, min_periods=1).median()
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,4))
    plt.plot(dwin.index, dwin.values, label='Daily mean')
    plt.plot(dwin.index, roll.loc[lo:hi].values, label='7-day rolling median')
    plt.axvline(day, ls='--', alpha=0.7, label='Anomaly day')
    plt.title(f'{sensor_id}: daily counts around {day.date()}')
    plt.ylabel('Pedestrians'); plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3); plt.legend(); plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    # Hourly profile: anomaly day vs same-weekday typical
    dfh = (pedestrian_counts_df[['sensor_name','sensing_date','hour','pedestriancount']]
             .query("sensor_name == @sensor_id")
             .assign(sensing_date=lambda x: pd.to_datetime(x['sensing_date']),
                     hour=lambda x: pd.to_numeric(x['hour'], errors='coerce')))
    dfh = dfh.dropna(subset=['hour'])

    dow = day.day_name()
    same_dow = dfh[dfh['sensing_date'].dt.day_name().eq(dow)]
    ref = same_dow[~same_dow['sensing_date'].eq(day)].groupby('hour', observed=False)['pedestriancount'].mean()

    an = dfh[dfh['sensing_date'].eq(day)].groupby('hour', observed=False)['pedestriancount'].mean()

    plt.figure(figsize=(8,4))
    ref.plot(marker='o', label=f'Typical {dow}')
    an.plot(marker='o', label=f'{day.date()}')
    plt.title(f'{sensor_id}: hourly profile — anomaly day vs typical {dow}')
    plt.xlabel('Hour'); plt.ylabel('Pedestrians'); plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3); plt.legend(); plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

plot_anomaly_window('Swa31', '2024-12-14')
plot_anomaly_window('BirArt1109_T', '2025-03-09')

On 14 December 2024, pedestrian volumes remained consistently higher than usual throughout the day, peaking in the evening—likely reflecting a large-scale Christmas event. On 9 March 2025, counts surged dramatically, with hourly peaks more than five times a typical Sunday, showing a clear event-driven anomaly. These cases confirm that extreme spikes are tied to special events rather than playground proximity.

Results¶

  • Pedestrian activity shows strong temporal patterns, with peaks during commute hours (8 AM and 5–6 PM), higher volumes from Wednesday to Saturday, and seasonal highs in March and December. Activity drops in June–July, aligning with colder weather.

  • Footpath availability is unevenly distributed: central areas such as Docklands, Carlton, and Parkville have dense networks, while suburbs like South Wharf, West Melbourne, and parts of East Melbourne show much lower coverage.

  • Suburbs such as Southbank, South Wharf, and Docklands have high pedestrian demand but limited footpath supply, creating pressure on existing infrastructure and potential safety risks.

  • A strong positive correlation (r ≈ 0.75) was found between footpath density and pedestrian activity, confirming that better walkable infrastructure supports higher levels of physical activity.

  • Playground proximity (≤800 m) did not consistently drive higher pedestrian volumes, showing that land use, connectivity, and transit access are more influential drivers of movement.

  • Event-driven surges dominate extreme anomalies, particularly on December–March weekends at riverfront and CBD locations (e.g., Southbank, Birrarung Marr), where volumes rose up to five times higher than normal days.

Recommendations¶

  • Invest in pedestrian infrastructure upgrades in high-demand, under-supplied areas (Southbank, South Wharf, Docklands, CBD) to improve safety, reduce congestion, and promote physical activity.

  • Enhance walkability networks by creating safer and more direct footpath connections between residential zones, recreational areas, schools, and public transport hubs.

  • Plan for event surges by integrating event schedules into city planning and deploying temporary pedestrian facilities, crowd management strategies, and clear signage during peak times.

  • Support year-round activity by improving pedestrian comfort in colder months with better lighting, shelter, and safer crossings to encourage continuous walking habits.

  • Prioritise equitable access by directing investment into suburbs with low footpath-to-pedestrian ratios, ensuring all communities benefit from safe and accessible walking environments.

  • Use finer-grain demographic and housing data (e.g., suburb or block-level profiles) to align urban density, particularly high-rise apartments, with adequate pedestrian infrastructure and open space provision.
